    bdr:NT06EFD59A6540C077
        a                   :Note ;
        :noteText           "this topic is applied to works which are concerned with the empowerments and propitiations of the seven buddhas:  \nthe seven hero buddhas are:  \n\n1) in the center rgyal ba sakya thub pa (sakyamuni) who makes the gesture of explaining the dharma;\n2) in the east rnam gzigs (vipasyin) who makes the earth touching and meditating gesture;  \n3) in the northeast gtsug tor can (buddha sikhin), who is boon granting and in meditation;  \n4) in the southeast thams cad skyob (buddha visvabhu) who is boon granting and in meditation;  \n5) in in the west 'khor ba 'jig (buddha krakucchanda) who makes the gesture of concentration;  \n6) in the southwest gser thub (buddha kanakamuni) explaining the dharma and in meditation;  \n7) in the northwest 'od srung (buddha kasyapa) whose right hand is boon granting and whose left is holding corner of his monks robe like the ear of a deer; all are golden in color and arrayed with all the marks and signs and wear the garments of the three robes of a monk; each sits in vajraparyanka at the foot of each's own bodhi tree; \n\ntheir attendants are:  \n8) to the south is blue khro bo chen po (mahakrodha, great wrathful one), palms folded with a noose inserted between them and a sword under the arm; he is complete with the dress of a wrathful deity; \n \n9) to the north is green, peaceful phyag na rdo rje (vajrapani) whose right hand is pressing a vajra to his heart and his left hand is resting on the seat; he sits in lalita, adorned with silk and jewels; \n\nat the four gates are 1) eastern dhrtarasta; 2) south virudhaka; 3) west virupaksa; 4) north vaisravana\n\nthis group of sadhana is is included in the group of transmissions from the 13th century indian master sakyaraksita; these were all received by taranatha from his master purnavajra; the lineage is different for deities of tibetan buddhism #258-260 which were received by purnavajra in south india from devasambhava.\n\nin this sadhana buddha vipasyin is sitting by a an asoka tree; conqueror sikhin is sitting before a white lotus; buddha visvabhu is sitting beneath a sal tree; brahmin krakucchanda is sitting by a sirisa tree; kanakamuni is sitting by a glomerate fig tree (udumbara); kasyapa is sitting beneath a banyan tree; supreme sakyamuni is sitting by a a pippala (asvattha) tree; gautama is the last to gain enlightenment\n\ndeities of tibetan buddhism #237-245"@en .
    
